## 5.3 KTU Examiner's Valuation Warning / Pitfall Callout

> [!WARNING]
> **Common Mistakes That Cost Marks in KTU Lab Exams:**
>
> 1. **Forgetting metadata row:** The first row of the triplet must always store $(m, n, k)$. Students often start data from index 0, missing the metadata. **Penalty: -2 marks.**
>
> 2. **Dimension mismatch check skipped:** In addition, students directly merge without verifying $A.m = B.m$ and $A.n = B.n$. Examiners deduct **-1 to -2 marks** for this.
>
> 3. **Storing zero-sum entries:** When two non-zeros cancel out (e.g., $5 + (-5) = 0$), students incorrectly include the zero in the result. **Penalty: -1 mark per occurrence.**
>
> 4. **Confusing transpose with addition:** Many students apply addition logic for transpose or vice versa. This is a **conceptual error** costing **-3 to -4 marks**.
>
> 5. **Not updating non-zero count:** After addition, the first row's third value must reflect the actual count of non-zero elements in the result. Forgetting this causes **-1 mark** deduction.
>
> 6. **Row-major order violation:** Triplets must be sorted by row index, then column index. Unordered entries lose **-2 marks**.

