## 5.4 Topic Recap & Important Things to Remember

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Rapid Revision Checklist for KTU Exam:**

- **Sparse Matrix Definition:** A matrix with significantly more zeros than non-zeros ($k \ll m \times n$).
- **Triplet Form:** Size $(k+1) \times 3$; first row = $(m, n, k)$; subsequent rows = $(i, j, value)$.
- **Transpose Rule:** $B[k].row = A[k].col$ and $B[k].col = A[k].row$; metadata swaps to $(n, m, k)$.
- **Simple Transpose Complexity:** $O(m \times k)$ — uses nested loops (outer: columns, inner: scan all elements).
- **Fast Transpose Complexity:** $O(m + n + k)$ — uses `count[]` and `index[]` prefix-sum arrays.
- **Addition Precondition:** Both matrices must have identical dimensions; else operation is invalid.
- **Addition Logic:** Three-way comparison using two pointers — if $A < B$ lexicographically, copy $A$; if equal positions, add values (skip if zero); else copy $B$.
- **Zero-Cancellation Rule:** In addition, if sum = 0, do **not** store the entry in the result.
- **Row-Major Order:** Triplet entries must always be sorted by row first, then by column.
- **Memory Saving:** Triplet uses $(k+1) \times 3$ integers vs $m \times n$ integers for dense form.
- **Common Applications:** PageRank (Google), Finite Element Analysis, Recommendation Systems, Graph adjacency storage.
- **Lab Tip:** Always test your code with edge cases — empty matrix (k=0), single element, and full matrix scenarios.
