## 1. Core Technical Definition & Intuitive Overview

### 1.1 Queue (Linear Queue)

> [!NOTE]
> **Formal Definition (KTU 2024 Syllabus Terminology)**
> A **Queue** is a linear data structure that follows the **FIFO (First In, First Out)** discipline, where insertion (Enqueue) occurs at the **rear** end and deletion (Dequeue) occurs at the **front** end. It is a special case of an ordered list where modifications are restricted to its two ends.

**Conceptual Analogy — "The Movie Ticket Counter"**

Imagine a queue of people waiting to buy tickets at a cinema counter:
- The person who **arrives first** stands at the **front** of the line.
- New people **join at the rear** (back) of the line.
- The **ticket is served to the person at the front** — they leave first.

This perfectly mirrors a Queue data structure: the oldest element (the one inserted first) is always removed first. There are no shortcuts — you cannot serve the last person before the first; everyone is processed in strict arrival order.

---

### 1.2 Deque (Double-Ended Queue)

> [!NOTE]
> **Formal Definition**
> A **Deque** (pronounced "deck", short for **Double-Ended Queue**) is a generalized queue in which elements can be **inserted or deleted from BOTH the front and the rear** ends. It combines the capabilities of both a stack (LIFO) and a queue (FIFO).

**Conceptual Analogy — "A Train with Removable Coaches"**

Think of a railway platform where coaches can be attached or detached from **either end** of the train:
- The **engine can pull a new coach** from the front.
- A **new coach can be added at the back**.
- Coaches can be **removed from the front or the back** as per operational needs.

A Deque works exactly like this — it's a flexible line where both ends are active. It comes in two restricted variants:
- **Input-Restricted Deque**: Insertion only at the rear, but deletion from both ends.
- **Output-Restricted Deque**: Deletion only from the front, but insertion from both ends.

---

### 1.3 Circular Queue

> [!NOTE]
> **Formal Definition**
> A **Circular Queue** is an advanced variant of the linear queue that connects the **last position back to the first position**, forming a logical circle. It overcomes the **"false overflow" / memory wastage** problem of the linear queue by treating the array indices modulo **MAX**.

**Conceptual Analogy — "The Roundabout Traffic Circle"**

Picture vehicles moving around a roundabout (traffic circle):
- Vehicles **enter** at any gap (Rear).
- Vehicles **exit** at their turn (Front).
- The circle **wraps around** — there's no dead end; once a vehicle leaves, that spot can be reused by new entries.

In a linear queue, even after deleting elements, the vacated front slots are wasted — new elements cannot use them. A Circular Queue **reuses these empty slots** by logically connecting index `MAX-1` back to index `0` using **modular arithmetic** `(rear + 1) % MAX`.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Syllabus Highlight — KTU Board Focus**
> Out of all three structures, the **Circular Queue** carries the highest weightage in KTU examinations because it tests the student's grasp of **modular arithmetic, boundary conditions, and pointer (index) management** — concepts frequently asked in viva voce and code-tracing questions.
