## 3. Step-by-Step Derivations & Analytical Matrix

### 3.1 Exhaustive C Implementation — Linear Queue using Array

```c
#include <stdio.h>
#define MAX 5

int queue[MAX];
int front = -1, rear = -1;

void enqueue(int x) {
    if (rear == MAX - 1) {
        printf("\nQueue Overflow! Cannot insert %d\n", x);
        return;
    }
    if (front == -1)         // first insertion
        front = 0;
    rear++;
    queue[rear] = x;
    printf("%d enqueued to queue\n", x);
}

int dequeue() {
    if (front == -1 || front > rear) {
        printf("\nQueue Underflow! Nothing to delete\n");
        return -1;
    }
    int item = queue[front];
    front++;
    if (front > rear)        // queue becomes empty
        front = rear = -1;
    printf("%d dequeued from queue\n", item);
    return item;
}

void display() {
    if (front == -1) {
        printf("Queue is empty\n");
        return;
    }
    printf("Queue elements: ");
    for (int i = front; i <= rear; i++)
        printf("%d ", queue[i]);
    printf("\n");
}

int main() {
    enqueue(10);
    enqueue(20);
    enqueue(30);
    display();
    dequeue();
    display();
    return 0;
}
```

**Step-by-Step Trace (MAX = 5):**

| Step | Operation | front | rear | Queue State |
| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |
| 0 | Initial | -1 | -1 | [ , , , , ] |
| 1 | `enqueue(10)` | 0 | 0 | [10, , , , ] |
| 2 | `enqueue(20)` | 0 | 1 | [10, 20, , , ] |
| 3 | `enqueue(30)` | 0 | 2 | [10, 20, 30, , ] |
| 4 | `display()` | 0 | 2 | Output: 10 20 30 |
| 5 | `dequeue()` | 1 | 2 | [ , 20, 30, , ] |
| 6 | `display()` | 1 | 2 | Output: 20 30 |

> [!WARNING]
> **Observation — The Wastage Problem**: After step 5, indices 0 is now empty forever. If we try to `enqueue(40)`, `enqueue(50)`, `enqueue(60)`, the queue reports **"Overflow"** even though slot 0 is free! This is the **false overflow** issue solved by the Circular Queue.

