### 3.2 Exhaustive C Implementation — Circular Queue using Array

```c
#include <stdio.h>
#define MAX 5

int cq[MAX];
int front = -1, rear = -1;

void enqueue(int x) {
    if ((rear + 1) % MAX == front) {
        printf("\nCircular Queue Overflow!\n");
        return;
    }
    if (front == -1)
        front = 0;
    rear = (rear + 1) % MAX;
    cq[rear] = x;
    printf("%d enqueued\n", x);
}

int dequeue() {
    if (front == -1) {
        printf("\nCircular Queue Underflow!\n");
        return -1;
    }
    int item = cq[front];
    if (front == rear)            // last element being removed
        front = rear = -1;
    else
        front = (front + 1) % MAX;
    printf("%d dequeued\n", item);
    return item;
}

void display() {
    if (front == -1) {
        printf("Circular Queue is empty\n");
        return;
    }
    printf("Elements: ");
    int i = front;
    while (1) {
        printf("%d ", cq[i]);
        if (i == rear) break;
        i = (i + 1) % MAX;
    }
    printf("\n");
}

int main() {
    enqueue(1); enqueue(2); enqueue(3); enqueue(4);
    display();
    dequeue(); dequeue();
    display();
    enqueue(5); enqueue(6);          // these fill the previously emptied slots
    display();
    return 0;
}
```

**Step-by-Step Trace (MAX = 5, where index 4 wraps to 0):**

| Step | Operation | front | rear | Logical State |
| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |
| 0 | Initial | -1 | -1 | Empty |
| 1 | `enqueue(1)` | 0 | 0 | [1, _, _, _, _] |
| 2 | `enqueue(2)` | 0 | 1 | [1, 2, _, _, _] |
| 3 | `enqueue(3)` | 0 | 2 | [1, 2, 3, _, _] |
| 4 | `enqueue(4)` | 0 | 3 | [1, 2, 3, 4, _] |
| 5 | `dequeue()` | 1 | 3 | [_, 2, 3, 4, _] |
| 6 | `dequeue()` | 2 | 3 | [_, _, 3, 4, _] |
| 7 | `enqueue(5)` | 2 | 4 | [_, _, 3, 4, 5] |
| 8 | `enqueue(6)` | 2 | 0 | [6, _, 3, 4, 5] — **wrapped around!** |
| 9 | `enqueue(7)` | 2 | 1 | [6, 7, 3, 4, 5] — **FULL** |
| 10 | `enqueue(8)` | — | — | **OVERFLOW** (since `(1+1)%5 == 2 == front`) |

**Derivation of "isFull" check:**

$$
\text{isFull} \iff (rear + 1) \bmod MAX = front
$$

The reasoning: a queue of size MAX can hold only MAX − 1 elements (one slot reserved). If moving the rear one step forward lands exactly on front, the queue is full. The formula `(rear + 1) % MAX` elegantly simulates this in a single arithmetic step.

**Derivation of "wrap-around" enqueue:**

$$
\begin{aligned}
rear_{new} &= (rear_{old} + 1) \bmod MAX \\
\text{e.g., if } rear_{old} &= 4,\ MAX = 5 \\
rear_{new} &= (4 + 1) \bmod 5 = 5 \bmod 5 = 0 \quad \checkmark
\end{aligned}
$$

