### **PART A — Short Answer Questions (3 Marks Each)**

---

**Q1. `[KTU University Exam - Dec 2023, Model Question]`**

**Differentiate between a Linear Queue and a Circular Queue. Mention the specific drawback of the linear queue that the circular queue overcomes.**

**Model Answer (3 Marks):**

| Aspect | Linear Queue | Circular Queue |
| :--- | :--- | :--- |
| **Memory Usage** | Slots once vacated are never reused | Vacated slots are reused via modular arithmetic |
| **Full Condition** | `rear == MAX - 1` | `(rear + 1) % MAX == front` |
| **Drawback** | Suffers from **false overflow** / memory wastage | **No wastage**; rear wraps to index 0 |
| **Time Complexity** | O(1) | O(1) |

**Key Drawback**: In a linear queue, after several `dequeue` operations, the front slots become empty. However, the `rear` pointer has already advanced to the end of the array. So even if there are empty slots in the front, the queue reports **"Overflow"** and refuses new insertions. This is called **false overflow**.

The **Circular Queue** solves this by wrapping the `rear` pointer back to index `0` using modular arithmetic `(rear + 1) % MAX`, thus reusing previously vacated slots. *(Full marks: complete the table with all four rows.)*

---

**Q2. `[KTU University Exam - Jun 2024, Model Question]`**

**What is a Deque? Explain the two restricted variants of a deque with one real-world application each.**

**Model Answer (3 Marks):**

A **Deque (Double-Ended Queue)** is a linear data structure that allows **insertion and deletion of elements from both ends** — front and rear.

**Restricted Variants:**

1. **Input-Restricted Deque** — Deletion can occur from both ends, but insertion is allowed only at the **rear** end.
   - **Application**: **Undo operation** in text editors where insertions are sequential (at rear) but deletions (undo) can occur anywhere.

2. **Output-Restricted Deque** — Insertion can occur from both ends, but deletion is allowed only from the **front** end.
   - **Application**: **Job scheduling in operating systems** where new jobs can be prioritized (inserted at front) but processed strictly in queue order (deleted from front).

