**(b) Trace the above program with the input sequence: enqueue(10), enqueue(20), enqueue(30), dequeue(), dequeue(), enqueue(40), enqueue(50), enqueue(60). Show the values of front, rear, and the queue state after each operation. (7 Marks)**

**Solution Trace Table:**

| Step | Operation | front | rear | Queue Contents (logical order) | Output |
| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |
| 0 | Initial | -1 | -1 | Empty | — |
| 1 | enqueue(10) | 0 | 0 | [10] | 10 inserted |
| 2 | enqueue(20) | 0 | 1 | [10, 20] | 20 inserted |
| 3 | enqueue(30) | 0 | 2 | [10, 20, 30] | 30 inserted |
| 4 | dequeue() | 1 | 2 | [20, 30] | 10 deleted |
| 5 | dequeue() | 2 | 2 | [30] | 20 deleted |
| 6 | enqueue(40) | 2 | 3 | [30, 40] | 40 inserted |
| 7 | enqueue(50) | 2 | 4 | [30, 40, 50] | 50 inserted |
| 8 | enqueue(60) | 2 | 0 | [60, 30, 40, 50] — wrap-around | 60 inserted |

**Key Observation**: In step 8, `rear = (4 + 1) % 5 = 0`. The new element 60 is placed at index 0, which was previously vacated. This demonstrates the **circular wrap-around** behavior that solves the false overflow problem of linear queues.

**Mark Distribution (7 Marks):**
- Correct step-by-step trace for steps 1-3: 2 marks
- Correct handling of dequeue operations (steps 4-5): 2 marks
- Correct circular wrap-around in step 8: 2 marks
