**(b) Compare the time and space complexities of the Linear Queue, Circular Queue, and Deque implementations. Which one would you prefer for a Round-Robin CPU scheduler, and why? (6 Marks)**

**Model Answer:**

**Complexity Comparison Table:**

| Data Structure | Time Complexity (All Ops) | Space Complexity | Memory Reuse |
| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |
| Linear Queue | **O(1)** | **O(n)** | ❌ No |
| Circular Queue | **O(1)** | **O(n)** | ✅ Yes |
| Deque | **O(1)** | **O(n)** | ✅ Yes |

All three structures offer **constant-time** operations because they use direct array indexing and pointer arithmetic — no traversal is required.

**Preferred Structure for Round-Robin CPU Scheduler: Circular Queue** ✅

**Justification (any 3 valid reasons, 2 marks each):**

1. **Memory Efficiency**: In a round-robin scheduler, processes are constantly added to the queue (newly arrived) and removed (after their time quantum). A linear queue would waste memory over time as processes leave; the circular queue **reuses vacated slots** via wrap-around.

2. **True Circular Iteration**: The scheduler naturally cycles through all processes in a circular fashion — each process gets a turn in a rotating order. The circular queue's structure **directly mirrors this behavior**, making the implementation intuitive and elegant.

3. **No False Overflow**: The CPU scheduler can run indefinitely without ever hitting a "queue full" condition due to false overflow. The circular queue ensures that as long as the scheduler doesn't have more than MAX processes simultaneously, it can run forever.

4. **Deterministic Performance**: O(1) enqueue and dequeue guarantee that scheduling decisions take predictable time, which is **critical in real-time systems** where missed deadlines cause system failures.

> [!WARNING]
> **KTU Examiner's Valuation Pitfall — Common Marks Deducted Areas**
> - **(−1 mark)** Forgetting the **boundary reset** when the queue becomes empty after dequeue (`front = rear = -1`). Many students set only `front = -1` and leave `rear` at its old value, causing the next `enqueue` to write into a wrong location.
> - **(−1 mark)** Using `(rear + 1) % MAX == front` for "isFull" **without** leaving one slot empty. If you use `front == rear` for both isEmpty and isFull, the logic becomes ambiguous and the examiner will deduct marks.
> - **(−1 mark)** Writing `front = (front - 1) % MAX` instead of `(front - 1 + MAX) % MAX` — in C, `%` of a negative number yields a negative result, which causes **array index out-of-bounds errors** at runtime.
> - **(−1 mark)** Failing to demonstrate **circular traversal** in the `display()` function — many students write a simple `for` loop that fails when the queue has wrapped around.
> - **(−2 marks)** Not handling the case where `front == rear` (single element) properly in deque's `deleteFront`/`deleteRear` — both pointers must be reset to -1 simultaneously.

