### **Topic Recap & Important Things to Remember (Rapid Revision Checklist)**

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Last-Minute KTU Exam Revision — Pin This Section**

- **Queue** = FIFO discipline; insertion at rear, deletion at front; linear implementation suffers from false overflow.
- **Circular Queue** = same FIFO logic but uses `(rear + 1) % MAX` and `(front + 1) % MAX` to enable wrap-around; one slot is sacrificed to disambiguate empty vs full.
- **Deque** = generalized queue; supports all four operations (`insertFront`, `insertRear`, `deleteFront`, `deleteRear`); can emulate both stack and queue.
- **isEmpty**: `front == -1` (universal across all three).
- **isFull**: `(rear + 1) % MAX == front` (circular/deque) OR `rear == MAX - 1` (linear).
- **Backward wrap**: Always use `(index - 1 + MAX) % MAX`, never `(index - 1) % MAX` — the latter produces negative indices in C.
- **Reset condition**: When `front == rear` and we delete, both must be set to `-1` to mark the queue as empty.
- **Time complexity**: All operations are **O(1)** for all three structures.
- **Real-world applications**:
  - Queue → Printer spooling, BFS traversal, CPU job scheduling.
  - Circular Queue → Round-Robin scheduling, circular buffers in streaming.
  - Deque → Sliding window problems, palindrome check, undo-redo systems.
- **Single slot sacrifice rule**: A circular queue of size MAX holds at most **MAX − 1** elements, never MAX. This is by design to resolve the empty/full ambiguity.
- **Initial state convention**: Always start with `front = rear = -1`. This sentinel value distinguishes "empty" from "has elements" cleanly.
