# Section 1: Core Technical Definition & Intuitive Overview

## 1.1 Formal Academic Definition

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Doubly Linked List (DLL):** A linear dynamic data structure in which each node contains three fields — a `data` field, a pointer to the **previous** node (`prev`), and a pointer to the **next** node (`next`). Unlike a singly linked list, it permits **bi-directional traversal** in **O(1)** time per step.

**Browser Navigation Simulation:** A classic application where each visited web page is modeled as a node in a doubly linked list. A `current` pointer tracks the user's present location, and operations such as *Go Back*, *Go Forward*, and *Visit New Page* are implemented as pointer manipulations on this list.

### Formal Node Definition (C Structure)

```c
typedef struct PageNode {
    char url[100];        // Stores the URL string
    struct PageNode *prev; // Pointer to previous page
    struct PageNode *next; // Pointer to next page
} PageNode;
```

The structural triad `(prev, data, next)` is the defining characteristic that makes the doubly linked list uniquely suited for browser history management, because real browsers demand symmetric backward and forward navigation.

## 1.2 Conceptual Analogy / Intuition

> [!NOTE]
> **Real-World Analogy — The Reading Trail Bookmark:**
> Imagine reading a printed novel. You place a bookmark on the current page. If you flip back, you walk left along the pages; if you flip ahead, you walk right. Now suppose the novel had a "magic thread" connecting every page to both its **predecessor** and its **successor**. Each time you visited a new page, you tied a knot linking the new page to the previous one. To go *back*, you simply follow the thread to the left. To go *forward*, you follow the thread to the right. The "current page" is your bookmark — that is precisely a **doubly linked list**.

**Browser Mapping:**

| Real Browser Component | Doubly Linked List Mapping |
|------------------------|----------------------------|
| Web page | `PageNode` |
| URL | `data` field of the node |
| **Back** button | `current = current->prev` |
| **Forward** button | `current = current->next` |
| Visited history | Traversal from `head` to `tail` |
| Current page indicator | `current` pointer |

## 1.3 Why Doubly Linked List and Not Singly Linked List?

A *singly* linked list can only walk **forward**; going back would require re-traversing from `head`, giving **O(n)** time. The DLL allows backward traversal in **O(1)** time, which is the performance contract expected from a browser. KTU examiners specifically test this justification in viva voce.

> [!TIP]
> **Memory Trade-off:** A DLL uses **3 pointers worth of memory per node** (prev, next, data pointer inside the structure) versus **2** for a singly linked list. This is an acceptable cost for the O(1) backward navigation guarantee.

## 1.4 Standard Metrics Used in This Experiment

- **Time Complexity of `goBack()`:** **O(1)**
- **Time Complexity of `goForward()`:** **O(1)**
- **Time Complexity of `visitPage(url)` (excluding forward-history deletion):** **O(1)**
- **Time Complexity of `visitPage(url)` (including worst-case forward-history deletion):** **O(n)**
- **Time Complexity of `displayHistory()`:** **O(n)** where n is the total number of nodes
- **Space Complexity:** **O(n)** — one node per unique visited page

