# Section 2: Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Formula Sheet

## 2.1 Operational Logic of the Browser Navigation System

The browser's behavior with a doubly linked list can be broken down into four primary operations. Each operation must handle edge cases that the KTU examiner is guaranteed to test.

### Operation 1: `visitPage(url)` — Visiting a New Web Page

**Logic Steps:**

1. Allocate a new `PageNode` dynamically using `malloc()`.
2. Copy the URL into the `data` field using `strcpy()`.
3. **Critical Rule:** If the user is currently on a page that has forward-history (i.e., `current->next != NULL`), visiting a new page **invalidates** that forward history — this matches real browser behavior. Free all nodes in the forward chain.
4. If the list is empty (`head == NULL`), set `head = current = newNode`.
5. Otherwise, link `newNode->prev = current`, `current->next = newNode`, and advance `current = newNode`.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Why forward history is destroyed on a new visit:** Real browsers (Chrome, Firefox, Edge) follow this exact behavior. If you go `A → B → C → B` and then visit `D`, the path `B → C` is destroyed. This is non-negotiable behavior in the KTU lab record.

### Operation 2: `goBack()` — Navigate to Previous Page

**Logic Steps:**

1. Check if `current == NULL` (empty list) or `current->prev == NULL` (no back history).
2. If either condition is true, print *"No previous page in history"* and return.
3. Otherwise, set `current = current->prev` and print the new current URL.

### Operation 3: `goForward()` — Navigate to Next Page

**Logic Steps:**

1. Check if `current == NULL` (empty list) or `current->next == NULL` (no forward history).
2. If either condition is true, print *"No forward page in history"* and return.
3. Otherwise, set `current = current->next` and print the new current URL.

### Operation 4: `displayHistory()` — Show Entire Browsing Session

**Logic Steps:**

1. Traverse from `head` to the end of the list using a `temp` pointer.
2. Mark the node pointed to by `current` with a special prefix (e.g., `→ [CURRENT]`).
3. Stop when `temp == NULL`.

## 2.2 KTU Formula Sheet / Cheat Sheet

| Operation | Best Case Time | Average Case Time | Worst Case Time | Space Used | Edge Case Handled |
|---|---|---|---|---|---|
| `visitPage(url)` | **O(1)** | **O(1)** | **O(n)** | O(1) extra | Forward history cleared |
| `goBack()` | **O(1)** | **O(1)** | **O(1)** | O(1) | `current->prev == NULL` |
| `goForward()` | **O(1)** | **O(1)** | **O(1)** | O(1) | `current->next == NULL` |
| `displayHistory()` | **O(n)** | **O(n)** | **O(n)** | O(1) extra | Empty list check |
| `freeAll()` (cleanup) | O(n) | O(n) | O(n) | O(1) extra | Avoid memory leak |
| Insert at tail | O(1) | O(1) | O(1) | O(1) | Empty list check |
| Delete forward chain | O(1) | O(k) | **O(n)** | O(1) extra | k forward nodes to free |

> [!NOTE]
> In the table above, **n** denotes the total number of nodes currently in the list, and **k** denotes the number of forward-history nodes deleted during a `visitPage` call. The pipe symbols are intentionally omitted to preserve the markdown table format — the vertical separators visually separate columns only.

## 2.3 Engineering Utility

This data structure is **not academic only**. Real-world engineering applications include:

- **Web Browsers** (Chrome, Firefox, Safari) — Back/Forward cache.
- **Text Editors** (Microsoft Word, VS Code) — Undo/Redo stacks often use bi-directional traversal.
- **Image Viewers** — Previous/Next image navigation.
- **Slide Presentation Software** (PowerPoint, Google Slides) — Backward/forward slide navigation.
- **Music Players** — Previous/Next track with full history recall.
- **Operating System File Explorers** — Back/Forward navigation buttons.
- **Mobile App Navigation Frameworks** — Stack-based or list-based screen history.

> [!TIP]
> **Memory Leak Warning:** A common KTU lab-record deduction is the absence of a cleanup function. After `exit(0)`, dynamically allocated memory is reclaimed by the OS, but a properly engineered program should call `freeAll()` for each node. Examiners specifically look for this in the record.

## 2.4 Pointer Rewiring Diagram (Conceptual)

When a new page is visited while a forward history exists, the pointer rewiring follows this strict sequence:

$$
\begin{aligned}
\text{Step 1:} \quad & \text{Free all nodes in forward chain} \\
\text{Step 2:} \quad & \text{current.next} \leftarrow \text{NULL} \\
\text{Step 3:} \quad & \text{newNode.prev} \leftarrow \text{current} \\
\text{Step 4:} \quad & \text{current.next} \leftarrow \text{newNode} \\
\text{Step 5:} \quad & \text{current} \leftarrow \text{newNode}
\end{aligned}
$$

