| 4 | Go Back | `google ⇄ wikipedia ←current ⇄ github` | wikipedia.org | No |
| 5 | Go Back | `google ←current ⇄ wikipedia ⇄ github` | google.com | No |
| 6 | Visit `stackoverflow.com` | `google ⇄ stackoverflow ←current` (github, wikipedia freed) | stackoverflow.com | **YES** |
| 7 | Go Forward | *No forward history* — print warning | stackoverflow.com | No |
| 8 | Go Back | `google ←current ⇄ stackoverflow` | google.com | No |

The pointer rewiring at **Step 6** is the most critical step:

$$
\begin{aligned}
\text{Before Step 6:} \quad & \text{google} \leftrightarrow \text{wikipedia} \leftarrow \text{current} \leftrightarrow \text{github} \\
\text{Free chain:} \quad & \text{free(wikipedia)}, \text{free(github)} \\
\text{After Step 6:} \quad & \text{google} \leftarrow \text{current} \leftrightarrow \text{stackoverflow}
\end{aligned}
$$

## 3.3 Time Complexity Derivation

For `visitPage`, the total time is bounded by two components:

$$
\begin{aligned}
T_{\text{visitPage}}(n, k) &= T_{\text{allocate}} + T_{\text{free forward}} + T_{\text{link}} \\
&= O(1) + O(k) + O(1) \\
&= O(1 + k) \\
&\le O(n) \quad \text{in worst case when } k = n - 1
\end{aligned}
$$

For `goBack` and `goForward`, the operation is a single pointer movement:

$$
T_{\text{goBack}} = T_{\text{goForward}} = O(1)
$$

For `displayHistory`, every node is visited exactly once:

$$
T_{\text{displayHistory}} = \sum_{i=1}^{n} O(1) = O(n)
$$

For the total memory footprint:

$$
S_{\text{total}} = n \times \big( \text{sizeof(char[100])} + 2 \times \text{sizeof(pointer)} \big) = O(n)
$$

> [!NOTE]
> **Why `O(k)` and not `O(1)` for visit?** Because when the user goes `A → B → C → B → D`, the forward chain `B → C` is destroyed, which requires iterating and freeing 1 node. In the worst case (going back to `head` and then visiting a new page), the entire forward chain must be freed. KTU exams expect this nuance.

