# Section 5: KTU 2024 Scheme Examination Question Bank & Topic Recap

## 5.1 Part A Questions (3 Marks Each)

### Question 1 `[KTU University Exam - Dec 2023, Model Exam]`

**Q: What is a doubly linked list? How does it differ from a singly linked list? Mention any one real-world application where DLL is preferred.**

**Model Answer:**

A **doubly linked list (DLL)** is a linear dynamic data structure in which each node contains three components: a `data` field, a pointer to the **previous** node (`prev`), and a pointer to the **next** node (`next`). This bidirectional linking permits traversal in both forward and backward directions.

**Comparison with Singly Linked List:**

| Feature | Singly Linked List | Doubly Linked List |
|---|---|---|
| Pointers per node | 1 (`next`) | 2 (`prev` and `next`) |
| Backward traversal | Not directly possible | **O(1) per step** |
| Memory per node | Smaller | Larger (extra pointer) |
| Insert at both ends | O(1) at head, O(n) at tail | **O(1) at both ends** |

**Real-world application:** **Browser back/forward navigation** — each visited page is a node, and the `current` pointer can move in both directions in **O(1)** time, which is exactly what a browser requires for instant back/forward operations.

---

### Question 2 `[KTU University Exam - June 2024, Series 1]`

**Q: When a user visits a new web page after navigating back, the forward history is destroyed. Justify this behavior with a pointer-level explanation.**

**Model Answer:**

When the user navigates back from a page (say, `C → B`) and then visits a new page `D`, the browser logically no longer has a valid "future" path. The chain that was previously reachable from `B` (i.e., `B → C`) becomes **orphaned**.

**Pointer-level justification:**

- The `current` pointer now resides on `B`.
- `current->next` is non-NULL and points to `C`.
- A new node `D` must be inserted as `current->next`.
- Therefore, the existing forward chain rooted at `C` must be **traversed and freed** to prevent memory leaks and to maintain the invariant that a doubly linked list has at most one path between any two nodes.
- After freeing, `current->next` is set to `NULL`, and `D` is linked via `D->prev = current` and `current->next = D`.

This matches the user expectation that the back/forward buttons should reflect the **current** navigation timeline, not a stale branch.

