### Question A (14 Marks) `[KTU University Exam - Dec 2023]`

**Q: Write a C program using a doubly linked list to simulate browser back and forward navigation. Support the following operations: (a) Visit a new URL, (b) Go back, (c) Go forward, and (d) Display the complete browsing history. Explain how the forward history is cleared when a new page is visited from a non-tail position.**

**Part (a) — Algorithm and Implementation [7 Marks]:**

```c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>
#include <string.h>

typedef struct PageNode {
    char url[100];
    struct PageNode *prev;
    struct PageNode *next;
} PageNode;

PageNode *head = NULL, *current = NULL;

PageNode* createNode(char *url) {
    PageNode *n = (PageNode*)malloc(sizeof(PageNode));
    strcpy(n->url, url);
    n->prev = n->next = NULL;
    return n;
}

void visitPage(char *url) {
    /* Clear forward history */
    if (current != NULL && current->next != NULL) {
        PageNode *t = current->next;
        while (t != NULL) {
            PageNode *d = t;
            t = t->next;
            free(d);
        }
        current->next = NULL;
    }
    PageNode *n = createNode(url);
    if (head == NULL) head = n;
    else {
        n->prev = current;
        current->next = n;
    }
    current = n;
    printf("Visited: %s\n", current->url);
}

void goBack() {
    if (current == NULL || current->prev == NULL) {
        printf("No previous page.\n");
        return;
    }
    current = current->prev;
    printf("Back to: %s\n", current->url);
}

void goForward() {
    if (current == NULL || current->next == NULL) {
        printf("No forward page.\n");
        return;
    }
    current = current->next;
    printf("Forward to: %s\n", current->url);
}

void displayHistory() {
    PageNode *t = head;
    int i = 1;
    printf("\n--- History ---\n");
    while (t != NULL) {
        printf("%s %d. %s\n",
               (t == current) ? "->" : "  ", i, t->url);
        t = t->next;
        i++;
    }
    printf("---------------\n");
}

int main() {
    int ch; char url[100];
    while (1) {
        printf("\n1.Visit 2.Back 3.Forward 4.History 5.Exit\nChoice: ");
        scanf("%d", &ch); getchar();
        switch (ch) {
            case 1:
                printf("URL: "); fgets(url, 100, stdin);
                url[strcspn(url, "\n")] = 0;
                visitPage(url); break;
            case 2: goBack(); break;
            case 3: goForward(); break;
            case 4: displayHistory(); break;
            case 5: exit(0);
        }
    }
}
```

**Part (b) — Forward-History Clearing Logic with Diagram [7 Marks]:**

When a user has visited `A → B → C`, then navigates back to `B`, and visits a new page `D`, the forward chain `B → C` is **destroyed** before `D` is inserted.

**State before the new visit:**

$$
\text{head} \rightarrow A \leftrightarrow B \xleftarrow{\text{current}} \rightarrow C \rightarrow \text{NULL}
$$

**Algorithm to clear the forward chain:**

$$
\begin{aligned}
\text{1. } & t \leftarrow \text{current.next} \quad \text{(i.e., } t = C \text{)} \\
\text{2. } & \text{while } t \neq \text{NULL:} \\
& \quad d \leftarrow t \\
& \quad t \leftarrow t.\text{next} \\
& \quad \text{free}(d) \\
\text{3. } & \text{current.next} \leftarrow \text{NULL} \\
\text{4. } & \text{Insert } D \text{ after current}
\end{aligned}
$$

**State after the new visit:**

$$
\text{head} \rightarrow A \leftrightarrow B \leftrightarrow D \xleftarrow{\text{current}} \rightarrow \text{NULL}
$$

This is the standard browser behavior. The time complexity of the clearing step is **O(k)** where k is the number of forward nodes; the overall worst-case for `visitPage` is therefore **O(n)**.

