### Question B (14 Marks) — Alternative Choice `[KTU University Exam - June 2024]`

**Q: (a) Explain why a doubly linked list is preferred over a singly linked list for implementing browser navigation. Write the `goBack` and `goForward` functions in C with proper edge-case handling. (b) Modify the program to also count and display the total number of pages in the history at any point.**

**Part (a) — Why DLL? + Navigation Functions [7 Marks]:**

**Justification:**

In a singly linked list, a node only knows its **successor**. To navigate backward, the program would have to restart traversal from `head` until it locates the predecessor of the current node, costing **O(n)** time per back operation. In a doubly linked list, every node already stores a `prev` pointer, allowing `current = current->prev` to execute in **O(1)** time. For a browser, which may be invoked thousands of times per session, this is the deciding factor.

**Navigation functions:**

```c
void goBack() {
    if (current == NULL) {
        printf("History is empty.\n");
        return;
    }
    if (current->prev == NULL) {
        printf("Already at the first page. Cannot go back.\n");
        return;
    }
    current = current->prev;
    printf("Navigated BACK to: %s\n", current->url);
}

void goForward() {
    if (current == NULL) {
        printf("History is empty.\n");
        return;
    }
    if (current->next == NULL) {
        printf("Already at the latest page. Cannot go forward.\n");
        return;
    }
    current = current->next;
    printf("Navigated FORWARD to: %s\n", current->url);
}
```

**Part (b) — Counting Pages in History [7 Marks]:**

Add a helper function that traverses the list and counts nodes:

```c
int countHistory() {
    int count = 0;
    PageNode *t = head;
    while (t != NULL) {
        count++;
        t = t->next;
    }
    return count;
}
```

Update `displayHistory()` to include the count:

```c
void displayHistory() {
    PageNode *t = head;
    int i = 1, total = countHistory();
    printf("\n--- Browser History (Total: %d pages) ---\n", total);
    while (t != NULL) {
        printf("%s %2d. %s\n",
               (t == current) ? "->" : "  ", i, t->url);
        t = t->next;
        i++;
    }
    printf("------------------------------------------\n");
}
```

**Time Complexity Analysis:**

$$
T_{\text{countHistory}}(n) = \sum_{i=1}^{n} O(1) = O(n)
$$

The count is recomputed on every `displayHistory` call, keeping the function self-contained. An alternative optimization is to maintain a `count` global variable that is incremented on `visitPage` and decremented on `freeAll`, reducing this to **O(1)** at the cost of bookkeeping. Both designs are acceptable in KTU evaluation.

