## 5.3 Topic Recap & Important Things to Remember

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Rapid Revision Checklist for KTU 2024 Lab Exam:**

- **Node Structure:** Always define `data`, `prev`, and `next` fields in the `struct` declaration.
- **Two Pointers to Track:** Maintain both `head` (start of the list) and `current` (user's bookmark) as global pointers.
- **Visit Operation Rule:** New page must be inserted **after `current`**, and the **forward chain must be freed** if any exists.
- **Edge Cases to Always Handle:**
  - Empty list (`head == NULL`)
  - At the start of history (`current->prev == NULL`)
  - At the end of history (`current->next == NULL`)
  - Single-node list (both `prev` and `next` are `NULL`)
- **Time Complexities to Memorize:**
  - `goBack()` and `goForward()`: **O(1)**
  - `visitPage()`: **O(1)** amortized, **O(n)** worst case
  - `displayHistory()`: **O(n)**
  - `countHistory()`: **O(n)**
- **Memory Management:** Always include a `freeAll()` cleanup function before `exit(0)`. Each `malloc()` must have a matching `free()`.
- **String Handling:** Use `fgets()` + `strcspn()` to safely read URL strings; never use `gets()` (deprecated and unsafe).
- **Why DLL, not SLL:** Backward navigation in DLL is **O(1)**; in SLL, it is **O(n)**. This is the single most important viva question.
- **Browser Semantics:** Visiting a new page after going back **invalidates** the forward history — this is mandatory, not optional.
- **Bidirectional Traversal:** DLL supports both `head → tail` and `tail → head` traversals; SLL only the former.
- **Pointer Rewiring:** When inserting, **always update both** `newNode->prev` and `current->next`; missing either will cause traversal failures.
- **NULL Termination:** The `head->prev` and `tail->next` are **always NULL**; this is the canonical DLL invariant.
- **Viva-Friendly Phrases:** *"O(1) backward traversal due to the prev pointer"*, *"forward history is destroyed to maintain a single linear timeline"*, *"each node has three components: data, prev, next"*.
- **Common Pitfall:** Confusing the `head` pointer with the `current` pointer when drawing diagrams. The `head` is **fixed at the start of the list**; the `current` **moves** with user navigation.

