## 1. Core Technical Definition & Intuitive Overview

### 1.1 Formal Academic Definition (KTU 2024 Syllabus Terminology)

A **polynomial** is a mathematical expression of the form:

$$P(x) = a_n x^n + a_{n-1} x^{n-1} + \dots + a_1 x + a_0$$

where each $a_i$ is called a **coefficient** and the corresponding $i$ is the **exponent (power)** of $x$. A **sparse polynomial** contains very few non-zero terms compared to its maximum degree, making array storage inefficient.

A **Singly Linked List (SLL)** is a linear, dynamic data structure where each element (node) contains data and exactly one pointer to the next node. When used to represent a polynomial, each node stores only one term $(a_i, i)$, eliminating the wasted memory of zero coefficients in an array-based representation.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU 2024 Definition (Board-Examiner Standard):**
> *Polynomial representation using a singly linked list is a dynamic storage technique in which each non-zero term of a polynomial is stored in a separate node containing its coefficient, exponent, and a link to the next term, with terms conventionally maintained in decreasing order of exponents for efficient traversal and arithmetic operations.*

### 1.2 Conceptual Analogy — Plain English Intuition

> [!NOTE]
> **Real-world analogy: "A Shopping List"** 🛒
>
> Imagine you go shopping and your list is `Milk → Bread → Eggs → Cheese`. Each item is a *node*, and the *arrow* pointing to the next item is the *link/pointer*. A polynomial using a linked list works exactly the same way:
> - Each *term* (like $3x^4$) is an *item* on the list.
> - The *arrow* points to the next term.
> - The *last item* points to **NULL** (the end of the list).
> - You can easily add a new term, remove a term, or rearrange the list — all without shifting the other items, unlike a fixed-size array.

### 1.3 The Node Structure — Heart of the System

Each node is a C-style **struct** with exactly three fields:

| Field | Purpose | Example Value (Term $5x^3$) |
|:------|:--------|:---------------------------|
| `coeff` | Stores the numeric coefficient | `5` |
| `exp` | Stores the exponent/power of $x$ | `3` |
| `next` | Pointer to the next node | Address of next node |

> [!TIP]
> **Memory efficiency gained:** For the polynomial $x^{1000} + 1$, an array needs **1001 slots**, but a linked list needs only **2 nodes**! This is why linked lists are the preferred representation for **sparse polynomials** — a key KTU 2024 viva question.

### 1.4 Why Linked List and Not Array?

> [!WARNING]
> **Common KTU Viva Trap:** "Why can't we just use an array?"
> - Arrays have a **fixed size** decided at compile time.
> - Inserting a new term in the middle requires shifting all elements.
> - Sparse polynomials waste enormous memory.
> - Linked lists solve all three: dynamic size, easy insertion, zero wastage.
