## 2. Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Formula Sheet

### 2.1 Mathematical Model of a Polynomial Node

A polynomial $P(x)$ of degree $n$ with $m$ non-zero terms is represented as a sequence of nodes:

$$P(x) \equiv \left[\,(c_1, e_1) \rightarrow (c_2, e_2) \rightarrow \dots \rightarrow (c_m, e_m) \rightarrow \text{NULL}\,\right]$$

subject to the ordering constraint:

$$e_1 > e_2 > e_3 > \dots > e_m \geq 0$$

where $(c_i, e_i)$ denotes the coefficient-exponent pair of the $i^{th}$ term.

### 2.2 Core Arithmetic Operations — Step-by-Step Logic

#### 🔹 A. Polynomial Addition — $R(x) = P(x) + Q(x)$

The algorithm uses a **two-pointer merge technique** (similar to merging two sorted arrays):

**Step 1:** Initialize two pointers `p1` and `p2` at the heads of the two polynomial lists.

**Step 2:** Compare the exponents at the current pointers:
- If `p1->exp > p2->exp` → the term at `p1` is unique to $P(x)$. Copy it to the result and advance `p1`.
- If `p1->exp < p2->exp` → the term at `p2` is unique to $Q(x)$. Copy it to the result and advance `p2`.
- If `p1->exp == p2->exp` → combine coefficients: $c_{new} = p_1\text{->}coeff + p_2\text{->}coeff$. If $c_{new} \neq 0$, add to result. Advance both pointers.

**Step 3:** After one list is exhausted, append all remaining nodes of the other list to the result.

#### 🔹 B. Polynomial Multiplication — $R(x) = P(x) \times Q(x)$

Multiplication is reduced to **repeated addition** by distributive law:

$$R(x) = \sum_{i=1}^{m} \sum_{j=1}^{k} \left( c_i \cdot d_j \right) x^{e_i + f_j}$$

**Step 1:** For each term $T_i$ in $P(x)$, create a temporary polynomial by multiplying $T_i$ with **every** term in $Q(x)$.

**Step 2:** Add this temporary polynomial to the running result using the **polynomial addition algorithm** defined above.

**Step 3:** Repeat until all terms of $P(x)$ are processed. The like terms automatically combine during the repeated addition phase.

### 2.3 KTU Formula Sheet / Cheat Sheet

| Concept | Formula / Rule | Time Complexity | Space Complexity |
|:--------|:---------------|:----------------|:-----------------|
| Node memory | $3 \times \text{sizeof(Node)}$ fields | — | $O(m)$ for $m$ non-zero terms |
| Degree lookup | Traverse to first node → `head->exp` | $O(1)$ (with sorted insert) | — |
| Polynomial Addition | Merge two sorted lists | $O(m + k)$ | $O(m + k)$ |
| Polynomial Multiplication | Nested loop + add | $O(m^2 k)$ worst case | $O(m k)$ |
| Display polynomial | Single traversal | $O(m)$ | — |
| Insert new term | Traverse to position | $O(m)$ | $O(1)$ extra |
| Combine like terms (during add) | $c_1 + c_2$ when $e_1 = e_2$ | $O(1)$ per pair | — |
| Skip zero-coefficient term | $\text{if } c_{new} = 0 \Rightarrow \text{do not insert}$ | $O(1)$ | — |

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Boundary Conditions to remember for KTU exam:**
> 1. If both lists are empty → result is `NULL` (representing polynomial `0`).
> 2. If coefficient sum is exactly `0`, **do not** create a node.
> 3. If one list is `NULL`, the result is the other list (short-circuit).
> 4. Exponents are assumed to be **non-negative integers** in the KTU syllabus.

### 2.4 Real-World Engineering Applications

> [!NOTE]
> - **Signal Processing:** FIR/IIR filter design uses polynomial operations on transfer functions.
> - **Computer Graphics:** Bézier curves and B-splines rely on polynomial arithmetic.
> - **Cryptography:** Polynomial-based ciphers (e.g., NTRU) use linked-list polynomial arithmetic.
> - **Scientific Computing:** Symbolic algebra systems (Mathematica, SymPy) use linked lists internally.
> - **Compiler Design:** Polynomial simplification is a sub-problem of expression optimization.
