**Q2.** `[KTU University Exam – June 2024]`
**Why is a linked list preferred over an array to represent a sparse polynomial? Give two reasons.**

**Model Answer:**

1. **Memory efficiency:** A sparse polynomial (e.g., $x^{1000} + 1$) has very few non-zero terms. An array would allocate $1001$ slots, but a linked list uses only $2$ nodes.
2. **Dynamic size:** A linked list can grow or shrink at runtime, while an array has fixed size decided at compile time, which may cause overflow for high-degree polynomials.
3. *(Optional third mark)*: Easy insertion/deletion of terms without shifting elements.

**Marks Distribution:** Reason 1 (1) + Reason 2 (1) + Example/justification (1).

