# 1. Core Technical Definition & Intuitive Overview

## 1.1 Formal Academic Definition

> [!NOTE]
> **Binary Search Tree (BST):** A Binary Search Tree is a node-based binary tree data structure where for each node, all keys in the **left sub-tree** are **less than** the key in the node, and all keys in the **right sub-tree** are **greater than** the key in the node. This ordering property, known as the **BST Property**, enables efficient search, insertion, and deletion operations.

A **Dictionary ADT (Abstract Data Type)** is a container that stores data items as **(key, value)** pairs, where each unique key maps to exactly one value. In the context of this experiment, the **key** is the *word* (lookup identifier) and the **value** is its *meaning*.

The combination gives us a **Lexicographic Dictionary** where words are stored in BST nodes, and an **in-order traversal** retrieves them in **alphabetical (sorted) order** — mimicking a physical English dictionary.

## 1.2 Conceptual Analogy / Intuition

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Real-world Analogy: An English-Thesaurus Phonebook 📖**
> 
> Imagine a physical dictionary. If you open it to any random page, the words on the left page are alphabetically *smaller* and those on the right page are *larger*. A Binary Search Tree works identically:
> 
> - Open the dictionary to a **middle word** (the **root** node).
> - If your target word is alphabetically **before** it, flip **left**.
> - If your target word is alphabetically **after** it, flip **right**.
> - Repeat this halving process until you find the meaning.
> 
> This halves the search space every step — which is why lookup is so fast: **O(log n)** on a balanced tree.

## 1.3 Key Terminology for KTU 2024

| Term | Definition |
|---|---|
| **Node** | A structure holding `word`, `meaning`, and pointers `left` and `right`. |
| **Root** | The topmost node; entry point for all operations. |
| **Leaf Node** | A node with no children (`left == NULL && right == NULL`). |
| **Sub-tree** | A tree formed by a node and its descendants. |
| **In-order Traversal** | Left → Root → Right; produces **sorted dictionary** output. |
| **Height (h)** | The longest path (in edges) from root to a leaf. |

