# 2. Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Formula Sheet

## 2.1 BST Property — The Foundation

For every node `N` with key `K`:
$$
\begin{aligned}
\text{All keys in } N.\text{left} &< K \\
\text{All keys in } N.\text{right} &> K
\end{aligned}
$$

This single invariant governs **every operation** (insert, search, delete, find-min, find-max).

## 2.2 Core Operations — Step-by-Step Logic

### 🔹 A. Insertion
1. Start at **root**.
2. If tree is empty, new node becomes the root.
3. Compare new `word` with current node's `word` using `strcmp()`.
4. If new word < current word → go **left**; if > → go **right**.
5. If equal → **update meaning** (duplicate handling).
6. Repeat until a `NULL` pointer is reached; insert node there.

### 🔹 B. Search
1. Start at **root**.
2. Use `strcmp(query, node->word)` to compare.
3. If `strcmp < 0` → go **left**.
4. If `strcmp > 0` → go **right**.
5. If `strcmp == 0` → **found**, return the meaning.
6. Reach `NULL` → word not in dictionary, return **NOT FOUND**.

### 🔹 C. In-order Traversal (Display Dictionary)
Recursively: `Inorder(left) → Print(node) → Inorder(right)`.
This yields words in **alphabetical order** — the dictionary's most desired property.

### 🔹 D. Find Minimum and Maximum
- **Minimum**: keep going **left** from the root until `NULL`.
- **Maximum**: keep going **right** from the root until `NULL`.

## 2.3 KTU High-Yield Formula Sheet

> [!NOTE]
> **Mandatory Table — Memorize for ESE & Lab Viva**

| Operation | Best Case | Average Case | Worst Case (Skewed) | Space |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| Search | $O(\log n)$ | $O(\log n)$ | $O(n)$ | $O(h)$ recursive |
| Insert | $O(\log n)$ | $O(\log n)$ | $O(n)$ | $O(h)$ |
| Delete | $O(\log n)$ | $O(\log n)$ | $O(n)$ | $O(h)$ |
| Traversal (All n nodes) | $O(n)$ | $O(n)$ | $O(n)$ | $O(h)$ stack |
| Min / Max | $O(\log n)$ | $O(\log n)$ | $O(n)$ | $O(1)$ iterative |

Where $n$ is the number of words and $h$ is the height of the tree.

**Height relationship for a Balanced BST:**
$$
h = \lfloor \log_2 n \rfloor
$$

**Worst-case height (right/left-skewed tree, e.g., inserting sorted data):**
$$
h = n - 1
$$

## 2.4 Real-World Engineering Utility

- **Compiler symbol tables** store identifiers using BSTs / Red-Black Trees.
- **Spell-checkers** and **autocomplete** systems rely on lexicographic BSTs.
- **Database indexing** (B-Trees, evolutions of BST) accelerates key lookups.
- **File systems** use balanced BST variants (AVL, Red-Black) for directory entries.

