#### 🔹 Model Solution for (b) — 7 Marks

| Aspect | Balanced BST | Skewed BST |
|---|---|---|
| Definition | Height $h \approx \log_2 n$ | Height $h = n - 1$ |
| Search Time | $O(\log n)$ | $O(n)$ |
| Insertion Time | $O(\log n)$ | $O(n)$ |
| Tree Shape | Bushy, evenly distributed | Resembles a linked list |
| Space Utilization | Efficient | Wasted; pointer-heavy list |

**Real-world scenarios (4 marks):**

- **Balanced BST** scenario: Random-order word insertions into a spell-checker dictionary (e.g., user typing unpredictable words). The expected height is logarithmic.
- **Skewed BST** scenario: Loading an existing alphabetically-sorted wordlist (e.g., `a, b, c, d, ... z`) directly into a plain BST without rebalancing. Each new word becomes the right child of the previous one, producing a right-skewed tree with $O(n)$ search time.

> This is why self-balancing trees like **AVL** and **Red-Black Trees** are used in production — they guarantee $O(\log n)$ even for sorted input.

