# SECTION 1 — Core Technical Definition & Intuitive Overview

## 1.1 Formal Academic Definition (KTU 2024 Syllabus Terminology)

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Sorting** is the process of rearranging the elements of a list (or array) into either ascending or descending order based on a chosen comparison key. In the context of **PCCSL307 — Data Structures Lab**, Experiment 2 mandates the *implementation, execution, and empirical comparison* of five classical comparison-based and non-comparison-based sorting algorithms: **Bubble Sort, Insertion Sort, Radix Sort, Quick Sort, and Merge Sort**.

The **number of steps** involved in each algorithm is a *deterministic metric* used to:
- Quantify the operational cost (time complexity proxy).
- Empirically validate the theoretical Big-O bounds.
- Provide a fair empirical benchmark for performance comparison.

A **step** is typically defined as one of the following atomic operations:
1. A single **comparison** between two array elements.
2. A single **swap** (or assignment) of array elements.
3. A single **increment** of a loop counter or index.

> [!NOTE]
> **KTU 2024 Convention:** In lab examinations, the *step counter* is usually a global `long int count` that is incremented on every comparison and every swap. The final `count` value is printed alongside the sorted array to enable empirical comparison.

## 1.2 Conceptual Analogy / Intuition

Imagine you have a **hand of 5 playing cards** face-down on a table, and you want them in ascending order:

| Algorithm | Real-Life Analogy |
|-----------|-------------------|
| **Bubble Sort** | Comparing *adjacent* cards repeatedly; the biggest "bubbles" to the right end — like bubbles in water rising to the surface. |
| **Insertion Sort** | Picking each new card and **sliding it backwards** into its correct position among the cards already in your hand (the way most humans sort playing cards). |
| **Radix Sort** | Sorting cards first by the **last digit**, then by the **tens digit**, then by the **hundreds digit** — without ever comparing two cards directly. |
| **Quick Sort** | Picking a **pivot card**, placing all smaller cards to its left and all larger cards to its right, then recursively doing the same on the two piles. |
| **Merge Sort** | **Splitting** the deck into single cards, then repeatedly **merging** two sorted mini-decks into one bigger sorted deck. |

## 1.3 The Empirical Step-Counting Principle

For the lab experiment, every algorithm is instrumented with a global counter. The empirical relationship is:

$$\text{Total Steps} \approx \text{Comparisons} + \text{Swaps/Assignments}$$

The theoretical expectations for input size $n$ are:

$$\text{Steps} = f(n) \quad \text{where} \quad f(n) \in \{O(n^2),\, O(n \log n),\, O(nk)\}$$

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Bold Constants to Remember:**
> - **Best Case Lower Bound** for any *comparison-based* sort: $\mathbf{\Omega(n \log n)}$
> - **Worst Case** for Quick Sort: $O(n^2)$ (already sorted input with bad pivot)
> - **Linear-time** sort exists: Radix Sort $= O(nk)$ where $k$ is the number of digits.
