# SECTION 2 — Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Formula Sheet

## 2.1 Algorithmic Logic Breakdown

### 2.1.1 Bubble Sort — The Adjacent-Swapper

**Logic Steps:**
1. Iterate $i$ from $0$ to $n-1$ (outer passes).
2. Iterate $j$ from $0$ to $n-i-2$ (inner adjacent scan).
3. If $a[j] > a[j+1]$, swap them — increment step counter.
4. Each comparison itself increments the step counter.
5. After each pass, the largest unsorted element settles at the end.
6. **Optimization:** Use a `swapped` flag to detect an already-sorted array (best case: $O(n)$).

### 2.1.2 Insertion Sort — The Card-Slider

**Logic Steps:**
1. Iterate $i$ from $1$ to $n-1$.
2. Store $a[i]$ in a temporary `key` variable.
3. Iterate $j = i-1$ down to $0$ while $a[j] > \text{key}$ — shift elements right.
4. Place `key` at $a[j+1]$.
5. Each comparison and each shift increments the step counter.

### 2.1.3 Radix Sort — The Digit-Distributer (Non-Comparison)

**Logic Steps:**
1. Find the **maximum** element to determine the number of digits $k$.
2. For each digit place (units, tens, hundreds, ...):
   - Use a **counting sort** subroutine (stable).
   - Bucket elements by the digit at that place.
3. After $k$ passes, the array is sorted.
4. Step counter: increments for each digit-extraction and each bucket-assignment.

### 2.1.4 Quick Sort — The Divide-and-Conquer Pivot

**Logic Steps (Hoare / Lomuto Partition):**
1. Choose a **pivot** (last element in Lomuto, middle in median-of-three).
2. **Partition:** rearrange so elements $< \text{pivot}$ are on the left, $\geq \text{pivot}$ on the right.
3. Recursively apply Quick Sort to the two sub-arrays.
4. Step counter: increments per comparison and per swap in the partition.

### 2.1.5 Merge Sort — The Splitter-Merger

**Logic Steps:**
1. **Divide:** split the array at the midpoint into two halves.
2. **Conquer:** recursively sort each half.
3. **Combine:** merge the two sorted halves into a single sorted array using a temporary buffer.
4. Step counter: increments per comparison during merging and per assignment.

## 2.2 KTU Formula Sheet / Cheat Sheet

| Algorithm | Best Case | Average Case | Worst Case | Space Complexity | Stable? | In-Place? |
|-----------|-----------|--------------|------------|------------------|---------|-----------|
| **Bubble Sort** | $O(n)$ | $O(n^2)$ | $O(n^2)$ | $O(1)$ | ✅ Yes | ✅ Yes |
| **Insertion Sort** | $O(n)$ | $O(n^2)$ | $O(n^2)$ | $O(1)$ | ✅ Yes | ✅ Yes |
| **Radix Sort** | $O(nk)$ | $O(nk)$ | $O(nk)$ | $O(n+k)$ | ✅ Yes | ❌ No |
| **Quick Sort** | $O(n \log n)$ | $O(n \log n)$ | $O(n^2)$ | $O(\log n)$ stack | ❌ No | ✅ Yes |
| **Merge Sort** | $O(n \log n)$ | $O(n \log n)$ | $O(n \log n)$ | $O(n)$ | ✅ Yes | ❌ No |

**Comparison Formula (for an unsorted array of size $n$):**

$$\text{Bubble/Insertion Steps} \approx \frac{n(n-1)}{2} + \text{swaps}$$

$$\text{Quick/Merge Steps} \approx n \log_2 n \quad (\text{log base 2})$$

$$\text{Radix Steps} \approx n \cdot k \quad \text{where } k = \lfloor \log_{10}(\max) \rfloor + 1$$

> [!NOTE]
> **Note on $\vert$ symbol:** The mathematical $\vert x \vert$ notation is rendered as `\vert x \vert` or `\mid x \mid` to preserve the markdown table structure.

## 2.3 Real-World Engineering Utility

| Algorithm | Real-World Application |
|-----------|------------------------|
| **Bubble Sort** | Almost none in production — used purely in **teaching**. Sometimes used in hardware where swaps are cheap. |
| **Insertion Sort** | Standard library `qsort` / Timsort uses insertion sort as a **base case for small sub-arrays** ($n \leq 16$). |
| **Radix Sort** | **Database indexing, suffix array construction, integer sorting** in linear time. Used in older punched-card sorters. |
| **Quick Sort** | Default sort in many **C/C++ standard library** implementations (e.g., `qsort` on Linux glibc uses a quicksort variant). |
| **Merge Sort** | The backbone of **Timsort** (Python, Java, V8 JavaScript) and external sorting on **disk/tape**. Used in `git`'s diff algorithm. |
