# SECTION 5 — KTU 2024 Scheme Examination Question Bank & Topic Recap

## 5.1 Part A — Short Answer Questions (3 Marks Each)

> **[KTU University Exam – Dec 2023, Model Paper]**

### Q1. Define the term "stability" of a sorting algorithm. Which of the algorithms in this experiment are stable? *(3 marks)*

**Model Answer:**
A sorting algorithm is called **stable** if it preserves the *relative order* of equal-key elements in the input.
- **Stable algorithms in this experiment:** Bubble Sort, Insertion Sort, Radix Sort, Merge Sort.
- **Unstable algorithm:** Quick Sort (because partitioning can swap equal-key elements).

---

### Q2. Why does Radix Sort achieve $O(nk)$ complexity while comparison sorts cannot beat $\Omega(n \log n)$? *(3 marks)*

**Model Answer:**
- **Radix Sort** is a **non-comparison** sort — it sorts by *examining the digit structure* of the keys (using counting sort as a subroutine) rather than comparing pairs of elements.
- The lower bound $\Omega(n \log n)$ applies only to **comparison-based** sorts, derived from the decision-tree model where each comparison yields a binary outcome.
- Radix Sort sidesteps this bound by exploiting the **positional representation of integers**, performing $k$ passes of linear-time counting sort.

---

