#### Model Solution — Part (b)

**Algorithm (Lomuto):**

```c
int partition(int a[], int low, int high) {
    int pivot = a[high], i = low - 1, j, temp;
    for (j = low; j < high; j++) {
        count++;
        if (a[j] < pivot) {
            i++;
            temp = a[i]; a[i] = a[j]; a[j] = temp;
            count += 3;
        }
    }
    temp = a[i + 1]; a[i + 1] = a[high]; a[high] = temp;
    count += 3;
    return i + 1;
}

void quickSort(int a[], int low, int high) {
    if (low < high) {
        int pi = partition(a, low, high);
        quickSort(a, low, pi - 1);
        quickSort(a, pi + 1, high);
    }
}
```

**Comparison:**
- Quick Sort uses $\approx n \log_2 n$ comparisons = $7 \times \log_2 7 \approx 19.6 \approx 20$ comparisons.
- Bubble Sort used **20** comparisons but with many more **swaps**.
- **Conclusion:** Quick Sort is asymptotically faster $O(n \log n)$ vs $O(n^2)$, and produces fewer swap operations on average, confirming its superiority in the lab.

