### QUESTION B (14 Marks) — Alternative Choice

**(a)** Implement **Merge Sort** in C with a step counter. For input `[38, 27, 43, 3, 9, 82, 10]`, show the recursion tree and final step count. *(7 marks)*

**(b)** Implement **Radix Sort** for the same input and report total steps. Why is Radix Sort linear in the number of digits? *(7 marks)*

#### Model Solution — Part (a)

**Algorithm:**

```c
void merge(int a[], int l, int m, int r) {
    int i, j, k, n1 = m - l + 1, n2 = r - m;
    int L[25], R[25];
    for (i = 0; i < n1; i++) { L[i] = a[l + i]; count++; }
    for (j = 0; j < n2; j++) { R[j] = a[m + 1 + j]; count++; }
    i = 0; j = 0; k = l;
    while (i < n1 && j < n2) {
        count++;
        if (L[i] <= R[j]) a[k++] = L[i++];
        else              a[k++] = R[j++];
        count++;
    }
    while (i < n1) { a[k++] = L[i++]; count++; }
    while (j < n2) { a[k++] = R[j++]; count++; }
}

void mergeSort(int a[], int l, int r) {
    if (l < r) {
        int m = l + (r - l) / 2;
        mergeSort(a, l, m);
        mergeSort(a, m + 1, r);
        merge(a, l, m, r);
    }
}
```

**Recursion Tree for $n=7$:**

```
