#### Model Solution — Part (b)

**Algorithm:**

```c
int getMax(int a[], int n) {
    int i, mx = a[0];
    for (i = 1; i < n; i++) {
        count++;
        if (a[i] > mx) mx = a[i];
    }
    return mx;
}

void countSortForRadix(int a[], int n, int exp) {
    int output[50], countArr[10] = {0}, i;
    for (i = 0; i < n; i++) countArr[(a[i] / exp) % 10]++;
    for (i = 1; i < 10; i++) countArr[i] += countArr[i - 1];
    for (i = n - 1; i >= 0; i--) {
        output[countArr[(a[i] / exp) % 10] - 1] = a[i];
        countArr[(a[i] / exp) % 10]--;
        count += 2;
    }
    for (i = 0; i < n; i++) { a[i] = output[i]; count++; }
}

void radixSort(int a[], int n) {
    int m = getMax(a, n);
    int exp;
    for (exp = 1; m / exp > 0; exp *= 10)
        countSortForRadix(a, n, exp);
}
```

**Why Linear in Digits:**
- Maximum element is $82$, requiring $k = 2$ digit passes.
- Each pass calls **counting sort** which is $O(n + 10) = O(n)$ for decimal digits.
- **Total:** $T = k \cdot O(n) = O(nk)$ = $2 \times 7 = 14$ base ops.
- This is **linear in the number of digits** because each pass processes the *entire array once*, giving a per-pass cost of $n$ and a total cost of $nk$.

