## 5.3 KTU Examiner's Valuation Warning / Pitfall Callout

> [!WARNING]
> **Common Mark-Deduction Pitfalls in PCCSL307 Lab Exam:**
> 1. **Forgetting to reset the step counter** before each sort — students often re-run sorts on an *already-sorted* array, getting artificially small step counts. **Penalty: 1–2 marks per occurrence.**
> 2. **Confusing `>` with `>=`** in partition — using `>=` instead of `<` in Lomuto's partition causes an off-by-one error and **wrong output**. Penalty: 2 marks.
> 3. **Forgetting to copy the array back** before running the next sort — students may sort an already-sorted array, skewing empirical comparison. Penalty: 2 marks.
> 4. **Not incrementing the counter on swaps** — only counting comparisons. Examiners expect *both*. Penalty: 1 mark.
> 5. **Hardcoding $n=5$ or $n=10$** without making the program general — fail to demonstrate generality. Penalty: 1–2 marks.
> 6. **Using $O(n^2)$ notation in lieu of actual step count** — examiners in PCCSL307 expect *printed* step counts. Penalty: 2–3 marks.

