## 5.4 Topic Recap & Important Things to Remember

> [!NOTE]
> **High-Density Revision Checklist — Must Memorize for KTU ESE & Lab Viva**

- ✅ **Bubble Sort**: $O(n^2)$ average/worst, $O(n)$ best with early-exit flag, **stable**, in-place.
- ✅ **Insertion Sort**: $O(n^2)$ average/worst, $O(n)$ best on nearly-sorted, **stable**, in-place. Excellent for $n \leq 16$.
- ✅ **Radix Sort**: $O(nk)$ time, $O(n+k)$ space, **stable**, NOT in-place. Requires integer keys.
- ✅ **Quick Sort**: $O(n \log n)$ average, $O(n^2)$ worst, **unstable**, in-place. Use randomized pivot to avoid worst case.
- ✅ **Merge Sort**: $O(n \log n)$ always, $O(n)$ auxiliary space, **stable**, NOT in-place. Used in external sorting.
- ✅ **Empirical step ranking** for the same input: `Quick ≈ Merge < Insertion < Bubble`, with Radix Sort being linear-only in $k$ (digits).
- ✅ **Lower bound theorem:** $\Omega(n \log n)$ for *any* comparison-based sort (decision-tree argument).
- ✅ **Step counting convention:** increment on every comparison and every swap/assignment.
- ✅ **Master Theorem Case 2** applies to Merge Sort: $T(n) = 2T(n/2) + \Theta(n) = \Theta(n \log n)$.
- ✅ **Stability** matters when sorting records with secondary keys (e.g., sort students by name, then by grade — must keep stable sort to preserve grade order).
- ✅ **In-place** means $O(1)$ extra memory; **stable** means equal-key order is preserved.
- ✅ For the lab, **always print the original array, the sorted array, and the step count** for each of the five algorithms.
- ✅ Always run all five algorithms on the **same input** (use `copyArray`) for a fair empirical comparison.
